                  <p class="ia-table-text">There is uncertainty over the number of pension policies with safeguarded-flexible benefits, that is, safeguarded benefits that are not traditional salary-related (for instance final salary) pensions. We have used as a proxy the number of pension policies which offer  members, whilst they are accumulating their pension benefits, a guaranteed rate at which they can convert their fund into a pension income at retirement, referred to here as GAR benefits. We only have data on GAR benefits and  we are not aware of any available data showing the incidence of other safeguarded-flexible benefits<authorialNote marker="3"><p class="ia-table-text"><b> Other examples of where a benefit is safeguarded and flexible that are not GARs are </b><b>cases where an occupational pension scheme offers members an option to purchase a scheme pension on the basis of pre-determined conversion factors</b><b>.  </b></p></authorialNote>. However, we understand from insights from industry consultation that GARs are by far the most common type of safeguarded-flexible benefits in scope of this policy. Therefore, we expect that data on GARs will be a reasonable proxy for safeguarded-flexible benefits as a whole.  This assumption was tested in the impact assessment accompanying the consultation in September 2016. There were no concerns raised by stakeholders that the  safeguarded-flexible benefits which are not GARs would have a significant impact on the costing of this policy change. However, we have carried out sensitivity analysis around  this assumption..                            </p>
