      <section eId="section_11">
        <heading>Risks and Assumptions</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Risks and Assumptions</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>70.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There is uncertainty around the estimated costs and benefits of these regulations due to limited data on the incidence of safeguarded-flexible benefits, the frequency that individuals will enquire about giving them up and the processes and costs involved in implementing the changes. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>71.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>To understand the risk that we are over or under-estimating the policy impact as a result of this uncertainty, we have conducted sensitivity analysis on the most influential assumptions that we have the least confidence in:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The proportion of trust-based GARs which are money purchase</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The proportion of those who proceed to give up GAR after enquiring</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The proportion of safeguarded flexible benefits which are GARs</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The cost of the current calculation method</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The upfront costs of implementing risk warnings in contract-based schemes</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The on-going cost per Risk Warning for contract-based schemes</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The on-going cost per Risk Warning for trust-based schemes</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>72.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The following section explains the basis for our current assumptions and the impact of adopting more optimistic or pessimistic assumptions. Table 7 at the end of this section summarises the findings. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>The proportion of trust-based GARs which are money purchase</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>73.</num>
          <content>
            <p>In the absence of any quantitative evidence on the breakdown of money purchase and non-money purchase GARs, there is a great deal of uncertainty around the estimate of the proportion of members and schemes with trust-based GARs that are non-money purchase (and thus in scope for these regulations). Our central estimate is 50%; if this is an under-estimate of the proportion that are non-money purchase, we will be under-estimating the number of GARs in scope for this policy. A lower number of trust-based schemes and individuals in scope would mean a lower benefit for providers (as a result of the simplified advice requirement), but this will be off-set by even lower costs as a result of fewer schemes facing familiarisation costs (in year 1 only) and schemes having to produce fewer risk warnings. Therefore a lower percentage of GARs being non-money purchase would mean we are currently over-estimating the cost to business. With no data to guide our assumption, we have tested a wide range around the central assumption; as an optimistic assumption we have assumed that 10% of GARs are non-money purchase; our pessimistic assumption is that 90% are non-money purchase. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>74.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Sensitivity analysis around these assumptions shows that the overall costs and benefits to business are not very sensitive to this assumption. Increasing the proportion of schemes that are non-money purchase to 90% only increases the net costs to business by £0.02m in year 1 and £0.01m in subsequent years. Reducing the proportion to 10% on reduces the net costs by £0.01m in each year. Therefore, although there is no evidence to support the assumption that 50% of trust-based schemes and members with GARs are non-money purchase, the assumption does not represent a significant risk to our estimate of the net cost of this policy. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>The proportion of those who proceed to give up GAR after enquiring</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>75.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We have assumed that 62.5% of those with GARs who ask about transferring or accessing their pension benefits flexibly proceed with that action. We have used this percentage to translate the estimated number of people who actually give up a GAR per year to the number of people enquiring (which is the total number that will require risk warnings). Our assumption is based on responses from two providers about the proportion of those with a GAR who enquire about flexibly accessing those benefits and then that go on to give up their GAR. One provider gave an estimate of 35% and another indicated a majority of theirs which we have interpreted as 90%; this gives an average of 62.5%.  If the true proportion of individuals who go on to access their GAR after enquiring is actually higher than 62.5%, it means that we will currently be over-estimating the total number who enquire – and as a result over-estimating the costs to business from producing the risk warnings and over-estimating the benefits to businesses from the simplified advice requirement. Overall we would currently be over-estimating the net cost to business. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>76.</num>
          <content>
            <p>To test how sensitive the estimated business impacts are to this assumption, we have assumed a pessimistic assumption of 90% and a most optimistic assumption of 35% (assuming our two responses are the upper and lower bounds). The results show that, if 90% of those members who enquire about accessing their GAR go on to give it up, the net costs to business will be 0.33m higher than we have estimated in year 1 and 0.66m higher in subsequent years. On the other hand if only 35% go on to give up their GAR; the net costs to business will be 0.83m lower in year 1 and 1.71m lower in subsequent years.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>77.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This suggests that the cost benefit analysis is reasonably sensitive to this assumption. Although there is uncertainty due to the low number of providers that responded to our request for information and the wide range in responses given by the providers that did give an estimate, we have sought to further test our assumption. The FCA<authorialNote marker="52"><p> FCA, Data Bulletin Issue 7, <a href="https://www.fca.org.uk/publications/data/data-bulletin-issue-7"><u>https://www.fca.org.uk/publications/data/data-bulletin-issue-7</u></a> </p></authorialNote> publishes statistics showing the proportion of those giving up their GAR out of the proportion taking some action with their pot (either giving up their GAR or taking up their GAR). Of those accessing their pension, 63% in Q4 2015 and 61% in Q1 2016 gave up their GAR. These statistics are not directly comparable as they will not capture those who enquired about accessing their GAR but then took no action (i.e. did not give up their GAR or take up their GAR) but would require a risk warning. Similarly, they would include any individuals who chose to take up their GAR without asking about other flexible options and so would not require a risk warning. Therefore the FCA statistics cannot be used as a direct substitute for the proportion of members who enquire about giving up their GAR and then subsequently give it up - but they do provide some support for our central assumption that 62.5% would give up their GAR after initially enquiring.  </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>The proportion of safeguarded flexible benefits which are GARs</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>78.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The policy applies to all safeguarded-flexible benefits but we only have data showing the incidence of GAR benefits, a particular type of safeguarded-flexible benefit (where members have a guaranteed rate at which they can convert their fund into a pension income at retirement). From consultation with industry throughout the policy development process, we understand that GARs are, by far, the most common type of safeguarded-flexible benefits in scope of this policy. Furthermore, in the impact assessment accompanying the consultation in September 2016, we assumed that the number of GARs could be used as a proxy for the number of safeguarded-flexible benefits and there were no concerns raised by stakeholders about this assumption. Therefore our central estimate is that the estimated number of GARs is a reasonable proxy for safeguarded-flexible benefits as a whole. However, if other types of safeguarded-flexible benefit do exist in non-negligible numbers, we may be under-estimating the number of firms and individuals affected by this policy.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>79.</num>
          <content>
            <p>As part of our sensitivity analysis, we have increased the estimated number of individuals and firms affected by the policy, to account for an unknown quantity of safeguarded-flexible benefits which are not GARs. While we believe that the number of additional safeguarded-flexible benefits will be very low for the reasons explained above, we do not have any data on the number of safeguarded-flexible benefits which are not GARs to guide our assumptions. It would be very difficult to gather robust evidence about the volumes of safeguarded-flexible benefits which are not GAR benefits. We understand from stakeholder forums that they are likely to be concentrated in particular types of scheme such as small schemes or older schemes. These account for a relatively small proportion of pension scheme members and have, historically, tended to be less engaged with the Department, recording lower response rates to surveys.  We would therefore need to communicate with a very large number of schemes to robustly estimate the frequency of such benefits, which would be time-consuming and costly. Moreover, schemes may not be able to access this information easily. The information that we require will be held in individual contracts and in a lot of older and smaller schemes this information may not be digitally available. Safeguarded-flexible benefits that are not GARs can potentially vary substantially in design which means trustees and scheme managers may have to seek legal advice on a case-by-case basis to establish if the benefits they provide to members qualify as safeguarded and flexible. Therefore obtaining this information may be burdensome for schemes. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>80.</num>
          <content>
            <p>As an upper estimate of the additional number of safeguarded-flexible benefits, we have tested the impact of assuming that only 80% of safeguarded-flexible benefits are GARs - therefore increasing our volumes by a factor of 1.25. The results show that this would mean higher costs for providers in producing and sending risk warnings, but also higher benefits as a result of the changes to the existing advice requirement. Overall the net costs to business would increase by £0.44m in the first year but fall by £0.55m in subsequent years. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>81.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This suggests that, even if there are an additional 25% of individuals and providers affected by the policy – and we think this is unlikely given that the insights provided during the consultation process suggested that GARs represent the vast majority of safeguarded-flexible benefits – the net costs to business would only fall by around half a million pounds per year in steady state. For this level of sensitivity it would be disproportionate to undertake further work to estimate of the precise number of safeguarded-flexible benefits which are not GARs, given the cost that this would represent for government and industry.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>The cost of the current calculation method</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>82.</num>
          <content>
            <p>As our central estimate we have assumed that the cost that schemes currently incur to carry out the complicated calculation to assess the value of a member’s GAR is £187.50. This is based on the average of estimates given by two providers in response to a request for information by DWP; one gave an estimate of £250 to £400 (average=£325) and the other gave an estimate of £50.  Given the range in their responses, there is uncertainty around the cost that the current method of calculation represents to providers. If we over-estimate the current cost, it means we will over-estimate the benefits to providers arising from the simplification of the advice requirement rules. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>83.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>In order to test the impact on the net costs to business if we over- or under-estimate the current calculation costs per case, we have conducted sensitivity analysis around this assumption, using £325 as the most optimistic assumption and £50 as the most cautious. Sensitivity analysis shows that if the current calculation method only costs schemes and providers £50 per case, the net costs to business will be £1.14m higher in year 1 and £2.26m higher in subsequent years. If, on the other hand, the true cost were as high as £325, the net costs to business would be £1.13m lower in year 1 and £2.27m lower in subsequent years<authorialNote marker="53"><p> The asymmetry between £2.26m higher and £2.27m lower is due to rounding in the final costing tables. </p></authorialNote>. This shows that the analysis is quite sensitive to this assumption. However, we are believe that £50 would be a very cautious estimate; firstly it is significantly lower than the estimate provided by the other provider, but secondly  because, during the consultation process to determine whether the calculation method should be altered, schemes reported that applying the specified calculation method gave rise to ‘significant practical and financial burdens’<authorialNote marker="54"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/555564/consultation-valuing-pensions-for-the-advice-requirement-and-introducing-new-consumer-protections.pdf"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/555564/consultation-valuing-pensions-for-the-advice-requirement-and-introducing-new-consumer-protections.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote>. Thus £187.50 remains our central estimate. </p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <content>
              <p><u>The upfront costs of implementing risk warnings in contract-based schemes</u></p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>84.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We have assumed a one-off cost of £175,000 for providers to implement the system changes needed to produce tailored risk warnings. This is based on the median response given by providers in response to question 5 in the consultation<authorialNote marker="55"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/555564/consultation-valuing-pensions-for-the-advice-requirement-and-introducing-new-consumer-protections.pdf"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/555564/consultation-valuing-pensions-for-the-advice-requirement-and-introducing-new-consumer-protections.pdf</u></a></p></authorialNote> which requested ‘information on the likely costs of the provision to issue risk warnings, both the initial transition and on-going costs’. Four providers gave numerical estimates of the set up costs that they expected to incur to meet these requirements. These estimates ranged from £50,000-£65,000 to £450,000.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>85.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Sensitivity analysis of these assumptions shows that the estimated net costs to business in year 1 are very sensitive to this assumption; adopting £57,500 as a most optimistic assumption and £450,000 as the most pessimistic leads to net costs that are £1.88m lower and £4.40m higher respectively. As this assumption relates to upfront costs, the costs in subsequent years are unaffected.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>86.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Given the risk around our estimated business impact as a result of this uncertainty, we sought to further test the assumption with other providers and industry stakeholders. This suggested that costs would be dependent on the complexity of the systems used by providers and so will vary – but that £450,000 is likely to be an outlier and does not reflect the costs that most providers would incur. This provided us with additional reassurance that taking the median estimate, £175,000, is appropriate. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>The on-going cost per risk warning for contract-based schemes</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>87.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We have assumed that after having made system changes in year 1, contract-based providers will only incur additional costs of £15 per risk warning produced. This is based on taking the median of the estimates provided in response to the consultation<authorialNote marker="56"><p>  <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/555564/consultation-valuing-pensions-for-the-advice-requirement-and-introducing-new-consumer-protections.pdf"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/555564/consultation-valuing-pensions-for-the-advice-requirement-and-introducing-new-consumer-protections.pdf</u></a></p></authorialNote>. Estimates ranged from £0 to £60-£100. Adopting an optimistic assumption that providers would incur no on-going costs would mean that net costs were £0.42m lower in year 1 and £0.86m lower in subsequent years. Alternatively using the most pessimistic assumption of £80 per risk warning would add £1.86m to the net cost in year 1 and £3.70m per year in subsequent years.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>88.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This suggests that the overall costs are sensitive to this assumption. However, the pessimistic scenario is based on an estimate from the provider who gave the lowest estimate of the upfront costs, perhaps suggesting that such high on-going costs would only occur where less comprehensive system changes were implemented. Given that we have assumed upfront costs of £175,000, it seems reasonable to assume that only limited on-going additional work would be required.  </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>89.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Furthermore, during the consultation process, providers did not raise concerns about the on-going financial burden that the new risk warnings would represent. Alongside the consultation, we published our initial estimates<authorialNote marker="57"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/555566/draft-impact-assessment-simplifying-advice-requirements-for-safeguarded-pension-benefits-and-introducing-new-consumer-protections.pdf"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/555566/draft-impact-assessment-simplifying-advice-requirements-for-safeguarded-pension-benefits-and-introducing-new-consumer-protections.pdf</u></a> </p></authorialNote> of the policy impact in order to seek providers’ views on our assumptions; we had assumed only ten minutes of an administrator’s time per case would be required to produce the risk warnings on an on-going basis – the equivalent of £3.26. In their formal consultation responses, the majority of providers did not provide any alternative estimate of the on-going costs or make any comments suggesting that our estimates were too low. Similarly, during stakeholder roundtable events held as part of the consultation process, we sought views on the likely impacts of these measures and explicitly asked for feedback on our estimated costs. The events did not raise concerns that the risk warnings would lead to high on-going costs for providers. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>90.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Therefore, although the sensitivity analysis showed that net costs were sensitive to the estimate of the on-going costs incurred by contract-based providers in producing risk warnings, the median figure remains our best estimate. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><u>The on-going cost per risk warning for trust-based schemes</u></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>91.</num>
          <content>
            <p>In the absence of any robust evidence about the on-going costs that would be incurred by trust-based schemes, we have made an estimate according to the processes that we expect that schemes would be required to carry out in order to comply with the regulations. Based on the activities described in the ‘Monetised and non-monetised costs and benefits’ section of this Impact Assessment, we have estimated that trust-based schemes would spend three hours per risk warning, at a cost of £57.15. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>92.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We did not receive any consultation responses providing further insight into the costs for trust-based schemes and these risk warnings are a new requirement specific to members with GARs so we do not have historic evidence on the costs of producing them. Given the uncertainty, we have conducted sensitivity analysis around this assumption and have tested an optimistic assumption of on one hour of work being required (with a corresponding cost of £19.05) and a pessimistic assumption of 5 hours work (with a corresponding cost of £95.25). The results show that using the optimistic assumption would only make net costs £0.07m lower in year 1 and £0.16 lower in subsequent years, while the pessimistic assumption would only make net costs £0.08m higher in year 1 and £0.15 higher in subsequent years. Therefore, although we do not have robust evidence to guide our assumption, it represents a low risk as it does not make a big difference to the overall net costs.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Summary </p>
          </content>
        </level>
