        <paragraph>
          <num>94.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Table 7 shows that the assumptions which have the largest impact on the estimated net costs to business are those relating to the upfront and on-going costs for contract-based schemes in producing risk warnings, particularly the latter as this would have an on-going effect over a ten year period. However, having sought inputs from providers through formal consultation, as well as making direct requests for further evidence to consolidate our assumptions, we are confident that we have made the best possible estimate of the costs that these regulations will impose on contract-based providers.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>95.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The assumptions relating to trust-based schemes have the least evidence behind them but, as the results in Table 7 show, these assumptions do not have a significant impact on our overall estimate of the net costs to business and therefore do not represent a significant risk in our analysis.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_12">
        <heading>Direct costs and benefits to Business</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Direct costs and benefits to Business </b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>96.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The proposal imposes a burden on businesses and is within the scope for one-in, three-out and the Business Impact Target (BIT). For the purposes of the BIT, net costs to business are to be presented in 2014 prices and discounted to 2015, in order for all policies to be compared using consistent pricing and discounting. Using a one year appraisal period from October 2017 and 3.5 per cent discount rate in line with the Treasury’s Green Book, we estimate that as a result of the increase in these direct costs to providers there is an Equivalent Annual Net Direct Cost to Business (EANDCB) worth -£1.6 million<b> </b>(2014/15 prices).</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
