      <section eId="section_14">
        <heading>Small and Micro Business Assessment</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Small and Micro Business Assessment </b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>98.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We do not expect that these regulations will have a disproportionate impact on small and micro businesses. Only a minority of small and micro pension schemes are expected to have non-money purchase GARs, and for many of these the work of familiarisation and implementing changes will typically be carried out by an administrator or another other service provider. Those small and micro schemes that do carry out the familiarisation and implementation costs in-house will typically have very few members who actively seek to give up a GAR. The numbers will be even smaller on a per year basis. We therefore assume small and micro pension schemes will be able to meet these requirements manually, and we estimate that the costs of complying with these regulations will be low. Small and micro businesses affected would also benefit from the simplification of the advice requirement. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>99.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The policy intent for tailored risk warnings is to ensure that all individuals with GARs are well-informed about their value before they make the decision to transfer or convert their pension pot and give up their GAR. Exempting any subset of pension providers from this requirement would risk some consumers not being informed of the value of their guarantee before giving it up. Granting small and micro businesses that offer safeguarded-flexible benefits a full exemption from the proposed cap would not be compatible with the aims of the policy. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>100.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The consultation did not provide any evidence that this policy would have a disproportionate impact on small and micro-businesses.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_15">
        <heading>Implementation of preferred options</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Implementation of preferred options</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>101.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The preferred option is Option 2 - to simplify advice requirements for safeguarded pensions benefits so that the £30,000 threshold for seeking advice is based on the transfer value of the benefits (as opposed to the amount required to provide for the member’s accrued benefits), and introduce a requirement for firms to provide tailored risk warnings.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
